node.text: As we all begin to socialize again safely post pandemic, taking your children out in public can be a disaster. As a mom to a toddler, I can completely relate. Join me in my discussion with child psychologist and PhD Dr. Tom Phelan as we discuss tactics, tips, and common pitfalls for child discipline in public!

node.text:
Dr. Amna interviews internationally renowned expert, author, and lecture on child discipline Dr. Tom Phelan, PhD on whining and pouting.

We discuss

why children do it 
common responses from parents
what children are trying to convey
different types of manipulation by children
goals of whining and pouting
what parents can do 
and best practices to avoid.

Lastly, a great Q&A session!

Disclaimer: I’m a pediatrician, but I don’t create & conduct vaccine trials. Like other pediatricians in my field, I rely on public health officials & organizations like CDC, Data Safety Monitoring Board, and ACIP for reccs on the data, plus evidence from the vaccine clinical trials run by scientists.

As of 12/3/2020, we do not have very young children in the vaccine trials. Typically, we start with vaccine trials in adults and if safe, move on to children.Typically, adolescents & older children are enrolled first. They can communicate to us what side effects, if any, they experience.Thereafter, if safe, we move on to younger children.

Typically, vaccines work equally well in adults & children.There are some differences in doses (for example, in the flu vaccine for children under 3 years of age).

“How do we know something bad won’t happen?” 

I really love @dr.noc ’s response here. We typically have a good understanding of the human body& response to vaccines. Even with an mRNA vaccine, we know it’s not able to physically alter human DNA & is overall being tolerated incredibly well. 

Typical serious adverse events that occur on the order of days to months, like antibody dependent enhancement or Guillan Barre Syndrome, & that’s why we have clinical trials-to evaluate for these. Thankfully, we haven’t seen these to date.

Also, consider the risks vs benefits ratio. At this time, long term effects of Covid are wide in variety & can be very serious.We haven’t seen those effects occurring in vaccine trials.The risks definitely appear to be bigger & more severe with contracting disease, rather than obtaining the vaccine.

“I don’t want to be the first one to take it.”

You won’t be. With >30K individuals in the Moderna trial & >40K in the Pfizer trial, many people have volunteered to take this vaccine before us.We’ve learned a lot from following our clinical trials & from the many thousands of individuals who’ve received these vaccines before us.

Again, I don’t have all the answers. I’m watching the ACIP slides & recordings, awaiting reccs just like others. But I have faith in our public health officials &believe they have society’s health &betterment in mind.

node.text:
I know this is a heated topic. And I also realize that it’s not an easy decision to make. In this video I am discussing some of the important reasons why it’s important for children to go back to school. We are also discussing the risk of children being in school, different strategies we can do for each age group to mitigate risks or limit the risk of transmission, and measures we can take for adults like the teachers and staff that are in schools.

I wish I could speak longer than 10 minutes because I have so much to say. This isn’t easy and it’s not a one-size-fits-all approach. We may even see hybrid models that use a combination of the precautions I mentioned and/or sending kids to school 3x a week with 2x a week learning from home. Each county and district will come up with a plan to meet appropriate precautions that are feasible with the resources it has.

If you’re a teacher, please comment below and tell me what measures your schools are taking to keep you and students safe.

If you’re a parent, comment and let me know how you feel about schools reopening. 

This is not a perfect situation, and we don’t have all the answers. I certainly don’t, but I do feel like we do this if we plan appropriately . I know we know more now than we do in March and good planning, public health protocols, funding, all of this goes into play to make this happen.

I know alot of parents have been worried about this so I wanted to address it, along with questions about activities for summer while social distancing.

In this video, I discuss:

-Health of most children today in quarantine or staying at home 
-Hygiene Hypothesis
-Ways we can continue to prime our immune system including vaccines, microbiome, and going outside
-Safe outdoor activities that are social distancing friendly

I don't believe this is forever. I believe we will find a way for science to overcome this. Until then, we owe it to all of us to do a part to decrease transmission of COVID. 

Hope this helps!

If you ask me how I’m doing, I’ll probably smile and say, “I’m good!” 
 
I love these two girls, more than I ever imagined I could love anything. 
 
But the frustration, overwhelm, and anxiety of juggling it all in motherhood is very real. 
 
Lately, I wish I could split myself in two, and while I’m at it, why not three, so I can finally get to some of that elusive self care in. 
 
Being completely honest, I’m a bit nervous of getting back to clinical work while I’m adjusting and discovering my new footing! 
 
Last time around, I went back full 100% after having Asiya (woohoo, perks of residency) into the peds ER, but I was also able to not work at all during my mat leave with her. 
 
This time, I’m a private practice owner and my own boss. 
 
I’ve learned owning your own business comes with liberties but also logistic difficulties. I have continued admin work throughout mat leave this last few weeks but will be starting back up seeing patients soon! 
 
I have to say pros and cons to both situations! 

Parents -When did you go back to work after having a baby?

Pediatricians are the nicest doctors…until we’re not. 
And now, we’re just a bit ticked off. 
 
So called “experts” claiming kids are being harmed by masks, emotionally academically, and psychologically.  
 
By a piece of cloth. 
Calling it a muzzle.  
Calling it child abuse.  
Saying children aren’t affected by COVID. 
 
And the estimated 40K children who have lost a parent to COVID-19? 
The children hospitals around the country that are packed? 
That’s all fake news? Conspiracies? 
 
I don’t deal in conspiracies and misinformation. I chose this profession to protect those most vulnerable who often don’t have a voice to speak up for themselves.  
 
Do you ask your optometrist for advice on which dishwasher to buy or a dentist on how to fix an air conditioner? 
 
Why are we allowing politicians to pass recommendations in a pandemic brought upon by an infectious disease?  
 
No, masks aren’t harming children. What has the very serious potential to harm is keeping our kids out of a safe classroom…just because someone wanted to win an election this year. 
 
Stop politicizing masks. 
Stop being selfish.  
Kids need to be in school so why not do it safely the way pediatricians and public health experts have been recommending?

This week, I was “cleared” at my six week postpartum check up!  
 
This really felt like a big deal for me. 
 
I had a very tumultuous postpartum period with a few healing complications after Asiya. 
 
It gave me some degree of trauma and fear of the postpartum period.  
 
I also had no idea what “normal” healing looked or felt like. 
 
So this time around, I was more proactive prenatally and postnally about my body and the changes it was enduring, advocating for myself and setting myself up with the right resources. 
 
I still have a ways to go. 
 
My core is weak. 
My upper body hurts all. the. time. from my bad posture trying to nurse and prepare food/feed/dress/entertain/read to/interact with my toddler. 
And I so badly miss lifting weights. 
 
I’m not there yet but excited to continue on my journey to feeling back to a little of my old self. 🥰
 
Also, wowza- 6 weeks has flown by!

𝙉𝙚𝙬𝙗𝙤𝙧𝙣𝙨 𝙖𝙣𝙙 𝙐𝙣𝙫𝙖𝙘𝙘𝙞𝙣𝙖𝙩𝙚𝙙 𝙑𝙞𝙨𝙞𝙩𝙤𝙧𝙨

I want to make this clear- This is YOUR personal decision.   

As a physician in the healthcare community and a pediatrician, I can tell you majority of us are advising that you only allow baby around vaccinated family members.   
  
It is your personal decision if you would also choose for those family members to be tested prior to seeing baby. 

Determining factors for me would probably be that individual family member’s behaviors during this time, masking practices given most recent CDC guidelines, prevalence of cases from where they’re traveling from, etc. (This is something I think is also reasonable, given high transmissibility of delta variant which is the major strain being seen in those infected in the US today.)
  
Again, this is all based on risk assessment and my professional opinion at this current time.  
  
I will also say, I have always advocated for a newborn to be around vaccinated family members, even if no pandemic. Both flu and Tdap, especially during the cold winter season where flu is most prevalent in the US, can still be transmitted to a new irn… so this isn’t new advice.  
  
If mom received vaccine during pregnancy: Maternal antibodies are transferred transplacentally. (One reason why it’s so important for our children today to remain up to date on all childhood vaccines for if/when they become parents in the future!)  
  
If mom received vaccine and is breastfeeding: You are also passing some antibody protection on to baby.  
  
If mother contracted COVID, some conferrence of antibody protection is possible but difficult to determine how much. Also, this is a much riskier route of possible protection to the infant.   
  
Newborns are a vulnerable age group so taking steps to prevent a serious illness is a smart idea. 

As a parent to a newborn, I’m continuing to take caution, even after getting vaccinated in pregnancy.  Some label me a “sheep” for doing so and guilt me for “destroying my kid’s childhood”, but those of us parenting in this pandemic know the choices we are making for our kids’ safety aren’t easy.💚💙
  
Newborn parents-how are you handling visitors?

node.text:
In Feb 2020, I started potty training Asiya. We started small, easing in. She showed all the readiness signs (see my IGTV with @happypottytime to learn what these are). 
 
It took ~6 mos to get the hang of it, and 10 months to achieve no daytime accidents. By that point, I was in my first trimester and getting over Covid. Tackling nighttime potty training was not high on my list of priorities.  
 
As the pregnancy progressed, I became even less inclined to work on nighttime training. There were so many other big changes on our horizon- stating school, a new big girl bed, and of course, a sibling. My mom gut and pediatrician intuition told me if I pushed something too hard, it would be the first thing to regress.  
 
As expected, we are dealing with some daytime potty regression, and I’m so happy I held off on nights! 
 
My tips for this- 
 
🚽Speak to your pediatrician. This should be one of the first things to do. You want to make sure there isn’t a medical cause for the regression. 
 
🚽Address the cause. For Asiya, the regression is likely bc of a new sibling, so we are spending individual time with her and working to involve her in Maryam’s routine. 
 
🚽Not making a big deal of the accident and limiting scolding and shaming-Remember, this is not intentional! It’s SO important to be supportive  during this time. 
 
🚽Being consistent & encouraging.  We are back to asking more often with gentle reminders. Dont feel you automatically need to go back to diapers. 
 
🚽 Reward systems in moderation. I’m not anti reward for potty in a sensible way. If she goes a day without an accident, we do a sticker at the end of the day or bigger reward if one week without an accident. 
 
🚽Check in with other caregivers. We’ve reviewed this plan with her nanny and her school teachers so we are all on the same page. 
 
Lastly, adjusting your own schedule with a new baby is difficult. You may find yourself with frayed emotions and of course, exhausted. Try to remain positive during this, and don’t view it as a large setback. You’re doing a great job!💚💙

𝗧𝗵𝗼𝘂𝗴𝗵𝘁𝘀 𝗳𝗿𝗼𝗺 𝗠𝘆 𝗙𝗶𝗿𝘀𝘁 𝗠𝗼𝗻𝘁𝗵 𝗮𝘀 𝗠𝗼𝗺 𝘁𝗼 𝗧𝘄𝗼: 
 
Baby Maryam is 1 month old today mA, and I feel like time is flying! There’s so many things that are easier and so many aspects that are harder this time around. 
 
🔻Whatever alone time I had had suddenly become…Scarcer 
🔻I think my head is going to explode sometimes from bouncing between multiple conversations  
🔻I am constantly forgetting things I need in the house (so unlike me who keeps lists everywhere) 
 
🔺Reading a book to a toddler while feeding a newborn isn’t as hard as it was in the beginning. 
🔺I am really enjoying the newborn period so much more this time around.  
🔺Since we already have established childcare for our first, the extra set of hands who knows my house, kids, and parenting preferences has been so helpful! 
 
Before most of my mental and physical energy was focused on my oldest, but now learning how to divide that focus and energy has been tough. In fact, that’s the hardest part for me-not the sleepless nights.  
 
Often, I really feel like I can only truly snuggle guiltlessly with Maryam when Asiya is distracted or not around. Then when the baby is down, I want to spend special time with Asiya as she’s adjusting to our newest addition. 
 
Motherhood is never easy, but I think I’m just a little wiser this time around, realizing what didn’t help last time- 
 
Personally, I’m being cognizant of any negative self talk, focusing on better communication between me and Zain, and of course-realizing this phase of a newborn and toddler is not forever.  
 
👇🏼Moms of multiples, feel free to share any advice below!

𝙀𝙞𝙙 𝙈𝙪𝙗𝙖𝙧𝙖𝙠!      
 
Not like usual Eid pics!     
      
This year’s Eid ul Adha, Zain worked & I’m still on mat leave, managing last two days without nanny, my parents, or Zain during the day….ie trying to find my footing as a mom of two!      
      
The morning went like:      
4:05 am-feed the baby      
4:45 am- try to put baby back down      
5:10 am- get into bed myself       
6 am- my alarm goes off      
  
*Try to fit in baby being fed, a shower, & my breakfast before Zain leaves at 7:15am for a full day of Mohs surgery, & I have to drop of Asiya & between a newborn cluster feeding 😳      
      
6:42am- baby fed & asleep. Somehow, I’m emptying my dishwasher and randomly trying to take swigs of coffee between shoving bites of breakfast in my mouth        
6:50am- Zain tells me to leave the dishwasher & go shower, but first I chug my coffee. Meanwhile Zain goes to get Asiya up at 7am        
7:22am- shower done, working on finishing my breakfast, still emptying that damn dishwasher (the spoons and forks, I hate that part), & finish feeding Asiya breakfast        
7:30am- Zain leaves for work & I start packing Asiya’s school stuff together (most of which I compiled the night before, trying to set myself up for success)        
7:40am- Zain calls & remembers he has a late start so he can take Asiya to school!      
      
The miraculous half hour I got to myself without having to figure out baby Maryam’s next feeding between Asiya’s school drop off was magical & an unexpected Eid gift for me! I blow dried my hair and just sat #smallwin      
    
I share all this to say, I am definitely struggling to find my footing as a mom of two as well! A friend of ours mentioned this & I would agree- becoming a parent for the 1st time was more mentally exhausting trying to learn how to fit a human into your daily lifestyle is with all its curveballs. Becoming parent to a 2nd is definitely more physically exhausting.

This picture was Zain and I, post my shower with a little concealer on so I looked semi normal in front of Asiya’s teachers, although I know they probably wouldn’t even care
    
Swipe to see the before shower real life look nowadays.🥴

The other day I shared I was making brownies during the girls’ nap time and got asked “when I’d be losing the baby weight?” 
 
When you put yourself out there on social media, you’re bound to get some …off the cuff comments.  🙄
 
Let me be clear-
This is legitimately not high on my list of priorities right now. 
 
This is what I know, in zero particular order bc I have little brain activity to craft a well organized post. 
 
▪️Less the number on the scale, I care more about feeling stronger again and getting back to regular exercise.
▪️I made quite a few modifications along the way of my workouts in this pregnancy and lifted less heavy which was fine by me.
▪️I will have a ways to go to get back to where I was in terms of my fitness level. 
▪️I’m a few pounds away from my “pre baby weight,” but I may never get back to that number, and THAT IS OK. 
▪️I went for my first solo walk this week, and it felt great. I loved getting outside! 
▪️Chugging water since I’m incredibly thirsty all the time from nursing yet all I want are carbs and coffee.  
▪️I thoroughly enjoyed the brownies I made the other day and celebrated my dads birthday with icecream cake over the weekend. I regret none of it- worth every bite! 
 
While my eating and sleeping schedules are off, I’m still *roughly* trying to abide by the 80/20 guideline..At the same time, definitely cutting myself slack. This morning, breakfast #2 was a croissant I picked up on a whim from the grocery store yesterday, and it tasted AMAZING.  
 
The only real exercise going on here is stretching during baby’s tummy time and occasionally working to engage my PF and TA (per reccs by my PT @create.your.core ). 
 
Just like the night awakenings and cluster feeds, this is a temporary phase. Of course, I will begin exercising again but in due time when I’m ready and medically cleared. My body just did it’s own marathon, growing a human mA and giving birth. I’m very lucky and grateful everything went well, and we are both healthy. 
 
It will take time to get back to where I was, and that’s normal! I’m amazed by the progress I’ve already achieved, but please- read the room before sending these messages.

Can’t believe it’s been almost a week since our little one arrived! 

When I contracted Covid in first trimester, let me tell you- I was a nervous wreck for a few days. 

There’s a downside to having too much medical knowledge…. But I also know everything happens for a reason, and we can only control so much.

Luckily, our course was uncomplicated, managed at home…. But that mom guilt kicked in immediately that somehow this was my fault and how it could impact the baby.

I was followed closely, and everything continued to look in the right direction, thank God.

Yes, I also made the decision with my husband and my OB to get fully vaccinated as well in pregnancy- shot # 1 in first trimester, shot # 2 in second trimester.

In fact, those vaccines gave me confidence to continue seeing Covid patients and testing others, especially as we saw more and more reassuring data from pregnant women receiving the vaccine and the positive effects on serum antibodies in newborns.

So here I am, still so in awe that alhamdolilah we are lucky to be blessed with a healthy baby girl. 

Of course, 4th trimester has its ups and downs, but you sweet Maryam have been perfect. You make us happier every day. 💙💚
